{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's \"Sair-e-Falak\" (\"Journey through the Spheres\"), the speaker ascends on a visionary path with Imagination as companion, traversing stars, the limits of dawn and dusk, paradisiacal visions (Iram, Tooba's birds, Houris, and saqi), before perceiving a remote \"dark abode\" of profound cold and emptiness beyond Paradise.[^1] The central vision-moment arrives when the angel Surosh reveals this as Hell itself—not a fiery realm, but an inherent void where damned souls must supply their own \"embers\" drawn from earthly deeds, instilling terror through self-reflection.[^2] Iqbal's speaker thus seeks metaphysical insight into divine justice and human agency in the afterlife.\n\nBy contrast, the speaker of the Old English \"The Wanderer\"—an exiled \"earth-stepper\" traversing wintry seas amid frost, hail, and sea-birds—contemplates earthly transience: ruined halls, slain warriors scattered by war, wolves, and birds, all under wyrd's inexorable decay, where \"all this earth's foundation becomes empty.\"[^3] The central vision-moment is the wise loner's inward turn, recognizing that true remedy lies not in worldly joys or lords (long lamented in dreams and memory) but in patient faith and seeking \"grace, comfort from the Father in heaven, where for us all stability stands.\"[^4] The Wanderer hopes for divine mercy amid inevitable loss.\n\nIqbal probes cosmic/spiritual architecture for self-originating truth; the Wanderer seeks eternal consolation beyond mutability.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Sair-e-Falak\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-44c8f4).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Sair-e-Falak\" [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-9d0a05).\n\n[^3]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^4]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).",
